The '''Bodongpa''' or Bodong tradition, is one of the smaller traditions of [[Tibetan Buddhism]] falling outside the classification of the four main schools.{{sfn|Sudbury|2008}}

==History==
Bodong E Monastery ({{bo|w=bo dong e dgon pa}}), located in Yutok ({{bo|w=g.yu thog}}), in modern Zhaxigang ({{bo|w=bkra shis sgang shang}}), [[Lhatse County]], was the main monastery of the Bodong tradition.<ref name=TBRC_Bodong-E>{{cite web | url=http://www.tbrc.org/#!rid=G244| title=bo dong e dgon pa |website=TBRC|publisher=[[Tibetan Buddhist Resource Center]]| accessdate =2014-11-08}}</ref> It was first established in 1049 by the [[Kadam (Tibetan Buddhism)]] teacher Mudra Chenpo ({{bo|w=bka 'dams pa dge bshes tra mu chen po}}).<ref>{{Cite book|title=བོད་ཀྱི་དགོན་སྡེ་ཁག་གཅིག་གི་སྤྲོད་མདོར་བསྡུས།|author=blo bzang chos ʼbyor|page= | publisher=mi rigs dpe skrun khang|isbn=9787105081936}}</ref>

Bodong tradition itself goes back to Bodong Rinchen Tsemo, who received teachings from Drubthob Semo Chewa. Its most renowned figure, often regarded as its founder, was the Bodong Penchen [[Lénam Gyelchok]] ({{bo|w=las rnam rgyal phyogs}}, 1376-1451),<ref>{{cite web|title=phyogs las rnam rgyal|url=http://www.tbrc.org/?locale=en#!rid=P2627|website=Tibetan Buddhist Resource Center|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> whose seat was at this monastery.  Bodong Penchen authored over one hundred and thirty-five volumes and is known as the most prolific writer in Tibetan history. His most famous work is the ''Compendium of Suchness'' ({{bo|w=de nyid 'dus pa}})  comprising one hundred and thirty-three volumes having about 500 folios (1000 pages) in each. The extensive version contains one hundred and ten volumes; the medium version, twenty volumes; the condensed version, two volumes; and the extremely condensed version, one volume and this encyclopaedic work is considered the foundation of the tradition.

[[Je Tsongkhapa]] studied at Bodong E Monastery with the Lotsawa Namkha Zangpo ({{bo|w=lo tsā ba nam mkha' bzang po}}),<ref>{{cite web|title=bo dong e dgon pa|url=http://www.tbrc.org/#!rid=G244|website=Tibetan Buddhist Resource Center}}</ref> who taught him the ''Mirror of Poetry'' ({{bo|w=snyan ngag me long}}).

A well-known [[tulku]] of this tradition is [[Samding Dorje Phagmo]], one of the few female incarnation lineages of Tibetan Buddhism.

==Religious establishments==
Bodong E Gonpa<ref name=TBRC_Bodong-E /> was almost completely destroyed during the [[Cultural Revolution]] {{sfn|Sudbury|2008}} though some parts survived because it had been turned into a granary{{sfn|Diemberger|2007}}

Nönga Abbey ({{bo|w=mngon dga' chos sde}}),<ref name=TBRC_Nonga-Chode>{{cite web | url=http://www.tbrc.org/#!rid=G1KR1549| title=Nonga Chode |website=TBRC|publisher=[[Tibetan Buddhist Resource Center]]| accessdate =2014-11-08}}</ref> in modern [[Tingri County]], [[Shigatse]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]].

Chöde Monastery ({{bo|w=chos sde dgon}}), [[Nyêmo County]], [[Lhasa]]. Founded in 750, converted to the Bodong school in 1250.<ref name=TBRC_Chode>{{cite web | url=http://www.tbrc.org/#!rid=G3303| title= Chode Gon|website=TBRC|publisher=[[Tibetan Buddhist Resource Center]]| accessdate =2014-11-08}}</ref>

Pelmo Chöding ({{bo|w=dpal mo chos lding}}) in [[Nyalam County]], Shigatse, Tibet Autonomous Region.

===Outside Tibet===
In 1989 the Pelmo Choding monastery (Porong Gompa) in exile was established at Dharamsala, India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pema-dorjee.org/porong-gompa/|title=Porong Gonpa | accessdate=2014-11-08}}</ref> A Porong Pelmo Choding monastery has also been built in Kathmandu, Nepal. These monasteries were established by Tibetans from the Porong region of south west Tibet to preserve the Bodong tradition.

